<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="240" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1688,1967]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1760,1786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fitzgerald" authorityYear="2020" box="[327,535,1760,1786]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Ditomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elongata">
<emphasis box="[327,535,1760,1786]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Ditomyia elongata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other Nearctic 
<taxonomicName box="[998,1102,1761,1786]" class="Insecta" family="Ditomyiidae" genus="Ditomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="240" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[998,1102,1761,1786]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Ditomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: Wings hyaline with macrotrichia unevenly distributed, basal third of wing with large bare areas (cell br+bm mostly bare) (
<figureCitation box="[388,453,1832,1858]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[362,1225,187,1763]" captionTargetId="figure-20@2.[362,1225,181,1766]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Wings. 1. D. elongata n. sp., holotype female. 2. D. euzona, male. 3. D. potomaca, female. 4. D. sohnsi n. sp., holotype male. Scale bars = ca. 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4412967" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4412967/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); antennal flagellomeres light grey-brown, contrasting with pale yellow scape and pedicel; scutum pale yellow with light brown stripes (
<figureCitation box="[701,769,1868,1895]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1927,1951]" captionTargetBox="[248,1341,528,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-181@5.[247,1341,525,1904]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. D. elongata n. sp., holotype female. 7. Habitus. Scale bar = ca. 1.0 mm. 8–10. Female terminalia. Scale bars = ca. 0.25 mm. 8. Dorsal. 9. Ventral. 10. Lateral. Abbreviations: c1, cercus one; c2, cercus two; s7, sternite seven; s8, sternite eight; s10, sternite ten; t7, tergite seven; t8, tergite eight, t10, tergite ten." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4412973" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4412973/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); female terminalia as 
<figureCitation box="[1023,1142,1868,1894]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1927,1951]" captionTargetBox="[248,1341,528,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-181@5.[247,1341,525,1904]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. D. elongata n. sp., holotype female. 7. Habitus. Scale bar = ca. 1.0 mm. 8–10. Female terminalia. Scale bars = ca. 0.25 mm. 8. Dorsal. 9. Ventral. 10. Lateral. Abbreviations: c1, cercus one; c2, cercus two; s7, sternite seven; s8, sternite eight; s10, sternite ten; t7, tergite seven; t8, tergite eight, t10, tergite ten." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4412973" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4412973/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Figs. 8–10</figureCitation>
with the ultimate segment of the cerci in lateral view relatively narrow and gradually tapered to a rounded point apically (
<figureCitation box="[1205,1288,1904,1930]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1927,1951]" captionTargetBox="[248,1341,528,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-181@5.[247,1341,525,1904]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. D. elongata n. sp., holotype female. 7. Habitus. Scale bar = ca. 1.0 mm. 8–10. Female terminalia. Scale bars = ca. 0.25 mm. 8. Dorsal. 9. Ventral. 10. Lateral. Abbreviations: c1, cercus one; c2, cercus two; s7, sternite seven; s8, sternite eight; s10, sternite ten; t7, tergite seven; t8, tergite eight, t10, tergite ten." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4412973" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4412973/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
); female fore tibia ~1.5 times as long as fore basitarsus (
<figureCitation box="[628,696,1940,1967]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1927,1951]" captionTargetBox="[248,1341,528,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-181@5.[247,1341,525,1904]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. D. elongata n. sp., holotype female. 7. Habitus. Scale bar = ca. 1.0 mm. 8–10. Female terminalia. Scale bars = ca. 0.25 mm. 8. Dorsal. 9. Ventral. 10. Lateral. Abbreviations: c1, cercus one; c2, cercus two; s7, sternite seven; s8, sternite eight; s10, sternite ten; t7, tergite seven; t8, tergite eight, t10, tergite ten." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4412973" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4412973/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="240">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
